---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { DOMAIN } from '../../data/site';

const title = "Body Fat Percentage Guide - Navy Method & Visual Scales | BodyCompOS";
const description = "Learn how to measure and track body fat percentage using the US Navy Circumference Method, calipers, and visual comparisons.";
const canonical = `${DOMAIN}/guides/body-fat-percentage`;

const schema = {
	'@context': 'https://schema.org',
	'@type': 'Article',
	headline: title,
	description: description,
	datePublished: '2026-06-25',
	dateModified: '2026-06-25',
	author: {
		'@type': 'Organization',
		name: 'BodyCompOS Editorial Board',
	},
	publisher: {
		'@type': 'Organization',
		name: 'BodyCompOS',
		logo: {
			'@type': 'ImageObject',
			url: `${DOMAIN}/favicon.svg`,
		},
	},
};
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical} schema={[schema]}>
	<section class="site-container py-10 sm:py-12">
		<!-- Breadcrumbs -->
		<nav class="flex mb-6 text-xs font-semibold text-muted-foreground gap-2" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
			<a class="hover:text-accent transition-colors" href="/">Home</a>
			<span>/</span>
			<a class="hover:text-accent transition-colors" href="/guides">Guides</a>
			<span>/</span>
			<span class="text-foreground">Body Fat Percentage Guide</span>
		</nav>

		<!-- Content Hero -->
		<div class="max-w-3xl">
			<p class="eyebrow">Measurement Methodology</p>
			<h1 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-black leading-tight sm:text-5xl text-foreground">
				Body Fat Percentage Guide <br/>
				<span class="text-success bg-gradient-to-r from-success to-accent bg-clip-text text-transparent">Navy Method & Tracking Strategies</span>
			</h1>
			<p class="mt-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
				Understanding your body fat percentage is essential for choosing the right training and nutritional strategy. This guide covers how to estimate body fat using the US Navy Circumference Method, skinfold calipers, and visual comparisons.
			</p>
		</div>

		<!-- Main editorial body -->
		<div class="mt-10 max-w-4xl grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_300px]">
			<div class="content-panel bg-card border border-border p-6 sm:p-8 rounded-2xl">
				<div class="prose-lite space-y-8 text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
					
					<section>
						<h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground mb-3">1. The Role of Body Fat in Programming</h2>
						<p>
							Body fat percentage represents the proportion of adipose tissue relative to total body weight. Knowing this value is key for calculating Lean Body Mass (LBM), Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR), and Fat-Free Mass Index (FFMI). 
						</p>
						<p class="mt-3">
							These metrics help you choose the right calorie targets and strategy, preventing you from bulking at high body fat levels (which can lead to excess fat gain) or cutting when body fat is already too low (which can cause muscle loss and hormonal fatigue).
						</p>
					</section>

					<section>
						<h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground mb-3">2. The US Navy Circumference Method</h2>
						<p>
							The US Navy Circumference Method (developed by Hodgdon & Beckett, 1984) is a reliable and accessible equation for estimating body fat without expensive laboratory tests. It uses height alongside neck, waist, and hip circumferences (for females) to estimate body density.
						</p>
						<p class="mt-3 font-semibold text-foreground">For Males (units in inches):</p>
						<p class="font-mono bg-muted/40 p-3 rounded-lg text-xs">
							BF% = 86.010 * log10(Waist - Neck) - 70.041 * log10(Height) + 36.76
						</p>
						<p class="mt-3 font-semibold text-foreground">For Females (units in inches):</p>
						<p class="font-mono bg-muted/40 p-3 rounded-lg text-xs">
							BF% = 163.205 * log10(Waist + Hip - Neck) - 97.684 * log10(Height) - 78.387
						</p>
						<p class="mt-3">
							To get accurate results, measure waist circumference at the navel, neck circumference below the larynx, and hip circumference at the widest point. Keep the measuring tape flat against the skin without pulling it tight.
						</p>
					</section>

					<section>
						<h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground mb-3">3. Other Estimation Methods</h2>
						<ul class="space-y-3 mt-3">
							<li>
								<strong>Skinfold Calipers:</strong> Measures subcutaneous fat thickness at specific sites (e.g., Jackson-Pollock 3-site or 7-site). Calipers are highly dependent on tester skill but are excellent for tracking progress at specific local sites.
							</li>
							<li>
								<strong>Bioelectrical Impedance (BIA):</strong> Found in smart scales and handheld devices. BIA is highly sensitive to hydration levels, food intake, and skin temperature, making it noisy for day-to-day tracking.
							</li>
							<li>
								<strong>Visual Comparison:</strong> Standard reference photos help estimate body fat ranges. While subjective, visual comparison is useful for verifying calculated values.
							</li>
						</ul>
					</section>

					<section>
						<h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground mb-3">4. Reassessment Guidelines</h2>
						<p>
							Because body fat measurements are estimates, treat them as trends rather than exact values. Measure circumferences every 2 to 4 weeks under identical conditions (e.g., first thing in the morning, fasted). Track changes in waist size and strength to evaluate your progress.
						</p>
					</section>

					<!-- YMYL Disclaimer -->
					<div class="border-t border-border pt-6 text-[10px] text-muted-foreground">
						<p><strong>YMYL Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for educational purposes only. Body fat equations are population estimates and can be affected by body shape and muscle distribution. Individuals with clinical health concerns or eating disorders should seek guidance from qualified healthcare providers.</p>
					</div>

				</div>
			</div>
			
			<!-- Sidebar -->
			<div class="space-y-6">
				<div class="surface border border-border p-5 rounded-2xl">
					<h3 class="font-bold text-sm text-foreground">Strategic Tools</h3>
					<p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground mt-2">Estimate your body fat percentage using our tools.</p>
					<a href="/calculators/body-fat-calculator" class="button-primary w-full text-center text-xs mt-4 block">Body Fat Calculator</a>
				</div>

				<div class="surface border border-border p-5 rounded-2xl">
					<h3 class="font-bold text-sm text-foreground">Related Guides</h3>
					<div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-xs">
						<a href="/guides/should-i-cut-or-bulk" class="block text-accent hover:underline">Cut or Bulk Matrix</a>
						<a href="/guides/body-recomposition" class="block text-accent hover:underline">Body Recomposition Science</a>
						<a href="/guides/protein-nutrition" class="block text-accent hover:underline font-semibold">Protein Nutrition Guide</a>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>
</Layout>
